follow_link_reasons: The spacecraft carries a gold-plated phonograph record, the Voyager Golden Record, containing sounds and images selected to portray the diversity of life and culture on Earth.
The record was selected by a committee chaired by Carl Sagan.
Sagan played key roles in NASA missions (including Mariner, Viking, Voyager missions) and chaired the committee that produced the Voyager Golden Record.
It includes links to the Planetary Society and the Pioneer plaque.
The Pioneer plaque is a pair of gold-anodized aluminum plates attached to the Pioneer 10 and Pioneer 11 spacecraft launched in the early 1970s.
The page links to interstellar space and the heliosphere.

Spacecraft such as Voyager 1 and Voyager 2 have provided in situ measurements indicating when they crossed the heliopause — the boundary where the solar wind's influence ends — entering interstellar space.
Observations by the Voyager spacecraft helped characterize these regions.
topic_switch_reasons: Following a coherent historical thread from human-made artifacts intended as messages to other intelligences (Golden Record and Pioneer plaque) through the people who designed them (Carl Sagan), out to the spacecraft that carry them (Voyager 1, Pioneer 10) and finally to the physical region those probes now explore (interstellar space and the heliosphere).
The mix of human culture (music, images) and hard space physics (heliopause, plasma) was engaging.
